msItem.note:
This is a previously unidentified copy of The Alchemical Waters of Saint Giles. For an edition of this work from other manuscripts, see Willy L. Braekman, 'The Alchemical Waters of Saint Giles: Text and Context', in Studies on Alchemy, Diet, Medecine and Prognostication in Middle English, Scripta: Mediaeval and Renaissance Texts and Studies, 22 (Brussels: Omirel, 1986), pp. 7-41. Braekman identifies Latin and vernacular versions of the work, including three English copies:
1. Cambridge, Trinity College, MS R.14.32, ff. 96r-98v;
2. London, British Library, Harley MS 2381, ff. 56v-60r;
3. London, British Library, Sloane MS 706, ff. 128v-132r. A similar work, not identified by Braekman, is extant in Cardiff, National Library of Wales, Peniarth 369, ff. 36r-38r entitled: Here bygynnyth doctor Gylys þe boke of vertuse and of wateres þat he made in deserte by þe which all sekenes curyd þat wer curabull. The connnection between St Giles and the nine waters is unclear, but Braekman suggests that the work may have been attributed to him because of cures that are described in his vita or because he, as the patron saint of blacksmiths, was associated with the furnace and the latter was also employed by alchemists (see Braekman (1986), p. 20). Additionally, the fact that this saint, according to his vita, lived near the mouth of the Rhône and the River Gard in Septimania, may have associated him with healing waters.
